vectorData.altText: 19. The red arrows in these images indicate an infarct of the _________  __________  __________  artery.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

That’s right!  The image shows the open medulla, identifiable by the pyramids ventrally and the inferior cerebellar peduncles dorsolaterally. Since the high signal area (white) is located dorsolaterally, this is an infarct of the posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA).

In order to understand the vascular territories associated with the medulla, you must meet two more arteries.
In this graphic, you see the vertebral arteries (A) giving rise to the posterior inferior cerebellar arteries (B). Notice artery C, the anterior spinal artery. It forms by the union of a ramus from each of the vertebral arteries. The anterior spinal artery is unpaired, and occupies the ventral median fissure.
Notice arteries D, the posterior spinal arteries. These bilaterally-paired arteries are variably branches of either the VAs or the PICA. The posterior spinal arteries descend in the dorsolateral sulcus, in the company of the dorsal rootlets.
Next we’ll look at cross sections of the medulla, and place these vessels around them in order to understand its vascular territories.
